{"key":"processedPost-10258853","value":{"id":10258853,"first":10257513,"last":14923768,"when":1241062222,"utime":"04/30/09 06:30 AM","cleanedPost":"Never make a casing layer OR bulk substrate without gypsum.&nbsp; It adds dramatically to the performance and weight of your flushes.<br />Gypsum isn't a pH buffer.&nbsp; It doesn't alter pH to a noticeable degree.<br />Gypsum supplies calcium and sulfur, both essential elements for good fruit body formation.&nbsp; It also keeps the substrate or casing layer loose.<br />You don't really even want a 'long term buffer' such as limestone in a casing layer.&nbsp; The life of a casing is measured in weeks, not months or years.&nbsp; I recommend the use of hydrated lime to get an <i>immediate</i> pH correction.<br />If your properly pasteurized casing layer is contaminating before first flush, it sounds like your spawn is contaminated.<br />If you're growing cubensis on a bulk substrate, no casing layer is needed, and not much will be gained from using one.<br />RR"}}